{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777814091548,"sessionID":"ses_212082fe0ffeVvRydscYchyCtZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"tool_write_jFhGGKcXeGqwxbaEV7oY","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gemini-3_1-pro-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r1s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r1s0\ntitle: \"Early JAL and precise load-use hazard detection\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The baseline suffers from a 2-cycle penalty for JAL instructions because they are resolved in EX. It also suffers from false load-use stalls when immediate fields happen to overlap with rs1/rs2 bit positions, degrading IPC on common patterns like LOAD followed by ADDI.\nhypothesis: |\n  We can resolve JAL in the IF stage, computing its target and redirecting next_pc immediately to save 2 cycles per jump. We can also pass the instruction down to the hazard unit to verify that rs1/rs2 are actually used by the opcode before stalling, eliminating false load-use stalls.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: high\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Detect JAL and compute jal_target_if to eagerly redirect next_pc when not flushing/stalling.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Suppress redirect for JAL (leaving it enabled for JALR and branches) since IF now handles it.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire if_id_w.instr into hazard_unit for opcode decoding.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Decode opcode to verify if rs1 and rs2 are actually read by the instruction before injecting a load-use bubble.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gemini-3_1-pro-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r1s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r1s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777814091536,"end":1777814091545}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":"**Exploring Microarchitectural Optimizations**\n\nI'm currently focused on identifying and proposing microarchitectural optimizations for the RV32IM CPU. The primary objective is to enhance its CoreMark iterations per second performance, building upon the existing 5-stage in-order pipeline.\n\n**Resolving Branch Delays**\n\nI'm digging into the branch resolution timing. Currently, branches are flushed for two cycles when taken because resolution occurs in the EX stage. My thinking is that if I can shift this resolution to the ID stage, I could shave off a cycle of penalty. This would involve forwarding data to the ID stage, which might impact the critical path, but the potential IPC gain seems significant.\n\n**Refining Branch Handling**\n\nI'm analyzing the branch penalty, currently two cycles due to EX-stage resolution. Shifting this to the ID stage for conditional branches is a possibility, though it might affect the critical path. However, I've realized unconditional jumps (JALs) could immediately benefit, reducing their penalty to one cycle by resolving them in ID without data dependency concerns.\n\n**Adjusting Branch Penalties**\n\nI'm refining branch handling. While conditional branches might introduce critical path issues if resolved earlier, I've identified that unconditional jumps (JALs) could immediately benefit. By resolving these in the ID stage, I can reduce their penalty from two cycles to just one, which should positively impact CoreMark performance due to frequent function calls.\n\n**Reducing Unnecessary Stalls**\n\nI'm analyzing load-use hazards and have identified a potential issue. The current hazard unit incorrectly stalls the pipeline for instructions like LUI or AUIPC that don't actually use source registers. I can fix this by modifying the hazard unit to check if the instruction in the ID stage actually uses `rs1` or `rs2`. This should eliminate spurious stalls and improve IPC.\n\n**Fixing Hazard Detection**\n\nI'm addressing spurious load-use stalls. The current hazard unit incorrectly stalls for instructions like LUI or AUIPC that don't read source registers. I'll modify the hazard detection to accurately check if `rs1` and `rs2` are actually used by the ID stage instruction, eliminating these unnecessary pipeline bubbles and boosting IPC.\n\n**Fixing Stalls**\n\nI'm focusing on eliminating unnecessary pipeline stalls. Specifically, I've identified that the hazard unit incorrectly halts the pipeline for instructions like LUI and AUIPC which don't actually utilize source registers. My plan is to adjust the hazard detection logic to accurately verify if `rs1` or `rs2` are indeed used by the instruction in the ID stage, thereby preventing these spurious bubbles and boosting IPC.\n\n**Adjusting Branch Resolution**\n\nI'm concentrating on reducing branch penalties. Unconditional jumps (JALs) can now be resolved in the ID stage, cutting their penalty from two cycles to one without impacting the critical path. This should provide a good performance boost for CoreMark.\n\n**Eliminating Stalls**\n\nI'm working to remove unnecessary pipeline stalls caused by the hazard unit. It incorrectly pauses for instructions like LUI and AUIPC that don't read source registers. I'll modify the detection logic to confirm register usage, preventing these spurious bubbles and improving IPC.\n\n**Optimizing Hazard Detection**\n\nI'm refining the hazard unit's logic. It currently causes stalls for instructions like LUI and AUIPC which don't actually use `rs1` or `rs2`. My focus is on adjusting the detection to accurately check for register usage in the ID stage, thereby eliminating these needless bubbles and enhancing IPC.\n\n**Optimizing Branch Handling**\n\nI'm focusing on reducing branch penalties. Unconditional jumps (JALs) can now be resolved in the ID stage, cu