{"type":"text","timestamp":1777814101808,"sessionID":"ses_212082fe0ffeVvRydscYchyCtZ","part":{"id":"prt_dedfa53500011yG76SBYIKeVs9","messageID":"msg_dedfa3895001LJwIb0wVP4BrsY","sessionID":"ses_212082fe0ffeVvRydscYchyCtZ","type":"text","text":"I have formulated a micro-architectural hypothesis to improve IPC and `CoreMark iterations/sec` without risking the critical path or cycle time. I've written the hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r1s0.yaml` for the orchestrator to process.\n\n### Hypothesis Summary\nThis proposal targets two low-hanging fruits that currently inject unnecessary pipeline bubbles:\n\n1. **Early JAL Resolution in IF Stage**: The 5-stage baseline currently resolves unconditional Jumps (JAL) in the EX stage, incurring a 2-cycle penalty on every subroutine call. By identifying `JAL` and computing its jump target directly in the IF stage, we can preemptively redirect the next PC immediately, effectively reducing the `JAL` penalty from 2 cycles to 0 cycles without impacting the critical path (since `JAL` has no register dependencies).\n2. **Precise Load-Use Hazard Detection**: The baseline `hazard_unit` naively compares the preceding `LOAD`'s destination register `rd` against the instruction's raw `[19:15]` (rs1) and `[24:20]` (rs2) fields. This causes a false 1-cycle pipeline stall if these fields—which often serve as immediates in instructions like `ADDI`, `LUI`, or `JAL`—happen to match the `LOAD`'s `rd`. By routing the opcode into the hazard unit and decoding whether the instruction actually reads `rs1` and/or `rs2`, we cleanly eliminate these false load-use stalls.\n\nBoth changes strictly fall under `micro_opt`, preserving the existing 5-stage topological layout while meaningfully increasing IPC.","time":{"start":1777814098768,"end":1777814101806}}}
