{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777814100723,"sessionID":"ses_212082f49ffeqUw8pes2tZpFt4","part":{"id":"prt_dedfa5af0001TuqItKVI0jFUGA","messageID":"msg_dedfa4902001kbEcAHoFnPmg3U","sessionID":"ses_212082f49ffeqUw8pes2tZpFt4","snapshot":"65a13379110e57b697b5f4099a0faf33b3edaed9","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777814102882,"sessionID":"ses_212082f49ffeqUw8pes2tZpFt4","part":{"id":"prt_dedfa5b00001D1E2ItrKa5FzG9","messageID":"msg_dedfa4902001kbEcAHoFnPmg3U","sessionID":"ses_212082f49ffeqUw8pes2tZpFt4","type":"text","text":"I have analyzed the current microarchitecture and identified a highly promising structural optimization. The baseline 5-stage pipeline suffers from two related inefficiencies:\n\n1. **Load-to-Store Penalty**: When a `STORE` consumes the data produced by an immediately preceding `LOAD` (e.g., `lw a0, 0(a1)` followed by `sw a0, 0(a2)`), the pipeline unconditionally stalls for 1 cycle because `rs2` is treated like an execution dependency. However, `STORE` only needs `rs2` in the MEM stage. By adding a bypass path in the `mem_stage`, we can forward the `LOAD` data directly from the WB stage into the memory write data multiplexer, entirely eliminating this 1-cycle stall.\n2. **False Load-Use Hazards**: The current `hazard_unit` blindly checks if `id_ex_rd` matches `if_id_rs1` or `if_id_rs2` without verifying if the instruction actually uses those registers. For example, if an independent `addi` instruction happens to have immediate bits `[24:20]` matching a preceding `LOAD`'s destination register, the hazard unit will trigger a spurious 1-cycle stall. We can safely eliminate these false stalls by decoding `uses_rs1` and `uses_rs2` directly from the opcode.\n\nI have generated and written the hypothesis YAML file to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r1s1.yaml`.","time":{"start":1777814100736,"end":1777814102880}}}
