ALU result, memory data).\n  // rvfi_commit_pc: PC of the committed instruction.\n  // rvfi_commit_instr: The committed instruction itself.\n  \n  // For now, let's just wire up some basic RVFI signals.\n  // A real implementation would need to capture the correct values from each stage.\n  assign rvfi_valid = mem_wb_w.valid; // Instruction committed if MEM/WB is valid\n  assign rvfi_pc_rdata = mem_wb_w.pc; // PC from the committed instruction\n  assign rvfi_id_rdata = mem_wb_w.instr; // Instruction from the committed instruction\n  // Result data needs careful selection based on instruction type (ALU, Load, etc.)\n  // For simplicity, we'll use the ALU result, but this is not fully correct.\n  assign rvfi_result_rdata = mem_wb_w.write_enable ? mem_wb_w.write_data : 64'b0; \n  assign rvfi_commit_pc = mem_wb_w.pc;\n  assign rvfi_commit_instr = mem_wb_w.instr;\n\nendmodule\n```\n\n**Implementing Branch Prediction**\n\nI am implementing a 32-entry PC-indexed Branch Target Buffer (BTB) with a 2-bit saturating counter. This predictor operates in the IF stage, combinatorially determining the next PC if a taken branch is predicted, aiming to reduce branch penalties without compromising Fmax. Logic to update the BTB from the EX stage is also under development.\n\n**Implementing Branch Prediction**\n\nI am implementing a 32-entry PC-indexed Branch Target Buffer (BTB) with a 2-bit saturating counter. This predictor operates in the IF stage, combinatorially determining the next PC if a taken branch is predicted, aiming to reduce branch penalties without compromising Fmax. Logic to update the BTB from the EX stage is also under development.\n\n**Implementing Branch Prediction**\n\nI'm implementing a 32-entry PC-indexed Branch Target Buffer with a 2-bit saturating counter. This predictor operates in the IF stage, combinatorially determining the next PC if a taken branch is predicted, aiming to reduce branch penalties without compromising Fmax. Logic to update the BTB from the EX