in `rs2` previously. I'm digging into why this discrepancy is occurring.\n\n**Investigating Data Path Inconsistencies**\n\nI'm tracking down a register read mismatch, specifically an `rvfi_rs2_rdata` discrepancy. My current focus is on whether the `hazard_unit` logic might be misinterpreting which registers are actually read by an instruction, potentially leading to incorrect forwarding behavior or an unexpected RVFI port output for non-read registers.\n\n**Investigating RVFI Specification Mismatch**\n\nI've discovered the root cause of the register read assertion failure. It appears the RVFI specification might expect `rvfi_rs2_rdata` to be valid when `rvfi_rs2_addr` is non-zero, irrespective of whether the instruction actually reads `rs2`. My `core.sv` baseline implementation reflects this by always outputting `instr[24:20]` as `rs2_addr`, which can be non-zero even for instructions like `ADDI`. This leads to mismatches when forwarding is not correctly handled for non-read `rs2` fields, causing assertion failures.\n\n**Clarifying RVFI Specification Compliance**\n\nI've pinpointed the RVFI specification mismatch. The baseline core incorrectly reports `rs2_addr` from `instr[24:20]` for instructions that don't actually read `rs2`, like `ADDI`. The RISC-V Formal spec requires this address to be zero in such cases. My implementation currently reflects the baseline's behavior, causing assertion failures when the formal verification expects a zero address.\n\n**Correcting RVFI Address Outputs**\n\nI've identified that my core incorrectly reports `rs2_addr` for instructions that don't actually read `rs2`, violating the RISC-V Formal spec. I'm now implementing a fix to ensure `rvfi_rs2_addr` is zeroed in such cases, aligning with formal verification expectations.\n\n**Correcting RVFI Address Outputs**\n\nI've identified that my core incorrectly reports `rs2_addr` for instructions that don't actually read `rs2`, violating the RISC-V Formal spec. I'm now implementing a fix t